{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"80d0b1c8-9a96-4ecc-9967-4fa544fdfc53","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Backgrounded | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| Closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is **iOS/Mac Catalyst only** — it fires when the system is about to snapshot the UI. Use it to save transient state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"27c375f2-f275-4d7b-a6b4-b74cfe9259f1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development - I can answer it directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"77E7:307F5D:81425D5:8F6EE7D:69EABE39"},"id":"ee488506-3f22-4daf-8f30-f64d0f929c17","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:50:10.758Z","parentId":"93493306-1b3f-4261-8ce4-b06437034aac"}
